# Why Do So Many Young People Like Communism?  
### A Comprehensive Analysis  

---

## Introduction  

In recent years, there has been a notable increase in favorable attitudes toward communism and socialism among young people, particularly within Generation Z and millennials in the United States. Various polls indicate that approximately 28-30% of Generation Z view communism and Marxism positively, with similar or higher percentages expressing support for socialism ([Abodo, 2021](https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-do-so-many-young-people-like-communism)). This trend raises critical questions about the underlying causes of this ideological shift, especially given the historical record of communism's association with authoritarian regimes and mass atrocities.

This report aims to provide a detailed, objective, and comprehensive analysis of why many young people today express favorable views toward communism. Drawing from multiple reputable sources, including polling data, expert analyses, and historical context, the report explores factors such as historical ignorance, economic dissatisfaction, educational influences, political rhetoric, and social dynamics. The report concludes with an informed opinion based on the evidence presented.

---

## 1. Historical Ignorance and Misunderstanding  

### 1.1 Lack of Awareness of Communism’s Historical Atrocities  

One of the most frequently cited reasons for young people's favorable views of communism is a significant lack of knowledge about the historical realities and human costs associated with communist regimes. For example, only about one-third of young Americans understand that the Chinese Communist Party has been responsible for more deaths than Nazi Germany ([Abodo, 2021](https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-do-so-many-young-people-like-communism)). Many are unaware of events such as:

- The Holodomor (1931-1934), a man-made famine in Soviet Ukraine that killed at least 3.9 million people ([Abodo, 2021](https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-do-so-many-young-people-like-communism)).
- Mao Zedong's policies, including the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution, which caused an estimated 50 to 70 million deaths ([Abodo, 2021](https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-do-so-many-young-people-like-communism)).
- The authoritarian nature of regimes such as Cuba, which, despite being less bloody, have provoked mass protests due to repression ([Abodo, 2021](https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/why-do-so-many-young-people-like-communism)).

Polls reveal that many young people confuse socialism with communism or Scandinavian-style social democracy, which features robust social welfare within capitalist frameworks. For instance, 31% of respondents in a Victims of Communism Memorial poll mistakenly believe socialism means a free market with social welfare benefits, akin to Nordic countries ([Johnson, 2020](https://www.acton.org/publications/policy-study/2020/10/23/half-gen-z-supports-marxism-socialism-heres-why)).

### 1.2 Educational Deficiencies  

The American education system has been criticized for failing to adequately teach the history of communism and socialism's failures. Surveys show that only 19% of Americans under 45 can pass a basic citizenship test, and many lack knowledge about key historical events such as the Holocaust or the Battle of the Bulge ([Zubatov, 2019](https://intellectualtakeout.org/2019/11/four-reasons-why-socialism-is-becoming-more-popular/)). Furthermore, curricula increasingly emphasize "woke" or revisionist histories that focus on America's flaws, potentially fostering cynicism and a distorted worldview ([Johnson, 2020](https://www.acton.org/publications/policy-study/2020/10/23/half-gen-z-supports-marxism-socialism-heres-why)).

